The manager must decide which division is a best fit for the different processes of the product.  Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scribbled with Sharpie onto her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian country ruled by a tyrannical militant junta who came into power in 1962 through the act of a coup d’état. In 2007 a number of street protests occurred, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests earned the name “The Saffron Revolution”, christened after the color of the robes that the monks wore. After the first few initial uprisings the public at large began taking an interest in the protests, and while at first the Burmese government begrudgingly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, soon the violence escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll rests at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republic Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

In my journey towards a career in social work, I am driven by a deep-seated passion to serve children and families who have experienced adversity, particularly those who have been abused or neglected. I am committed to the Division of Family and Children Services, where I wish to make a meaningful impact. The values that I bring to the table are service, respect, ethical integrity, and a dedication to fostering healthier relationships, both within families and in my professional development. These values are not merely professional aspirations; they are deeply personal convictions.

My path to this decision has been a winding one. Throughout high school and college, I witnessed numerous individuals grappling with their problems, often in unhealthy ways. This inspired me to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology, a field I felt could equip me with the necessary tools to understand and help others. However, I remained uncertain about my career path after graduation. It was during a summer break, visiting a friend, that I encountered a sixteen-year-old boy seeking refuge from his abusive parents. The following day, I learned that he had reported his situation to the police. Seeing an opportunity to assist, I offered my help, explaining my background to the officers. They requested my intervention, as they felt limited by their legal constraints. When I spoke to the parents, they seemed evasive, labeling their son's distress as a "manipulative" behavior. This experience solidified my desire to pursue a career in social work, where I could contribute more effectively to helping children navigate such complex family dynamics.

Social justice is another value that resonates deeply with me. While society often pays lip service to the importance of the individual, we are often encouraged to conform to societal norms. I choose to embrace my individuality and challenge these norms. Throughout my academic journey, I have stood up against social injustices, whether by expressing my unique identity, advocating for equality, or challenging discriminatory behavior. I am committed to advocating for social justice both within and beyond the social work field.

The following document delves into the Biological and Sociocultural paradigms concerning insomnia. Biological models concentrate on inherited genetic information and health-related aspects, while Sociocultural models explore environmental ties with race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia examines these models, explaining selected research to relate and elucidate them. The research explanations and findings are then critically evaluated for their specific strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized into primary, secondary, or other categories. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias; secondary disorders are linked to Axis I or Axis II mental disorders. Other sleep disorders can stem from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias encompass Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia hinders adequate or continuous sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia makes staying awake difficult for at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM episodes. Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, whereas Parasomnias pertain to behavioral abnormalities or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Mental disorder-related sleep difficulties arise from Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders, Mental Retardation). The following review centers on insomnia and also addresses primary sleep disorders in relation to the Biological and Sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, inheritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice found that phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons control sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, while inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. A GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep duration in mice (Matsuki et al., 2009). This suggests animal models can be generalized to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the human GABAB receptor. A disruption or absence of this receptor could impair adequate sleep without medication. Socioculturally, if the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and alterations would naturally disrupt sleep, impacting daily life aspects that require focus and endurance.

This document delves into the three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with an overview of the disorder, followed by a detailed explanation of its diagnosis, which includes common indicators or "warning signs". The paper concludes with strategies for a teacher in a mainstream classroom to support a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), pertains to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. In essence, CAPD is a disorder wherein the brain's ability to process sounds, particularly separating words and discerning conversation from background noise, is impaired. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing but struggle due to their brain's inadequacy in interpreting auditory information.

	The roots of CAPD date back to the mid-1950s, initially labeled "auditory imperception" by researchers investigating communicative disorders. An Italian research team, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, initiated diagnostic tests for these children in 1954. Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing in 1961 further advanced understanding of the disorder's physiological basis, while a 1977 conference sparked broader research on CAPD.

	Symptoms of CAPD include difficulty localizing or recognizing sounds, distinguishing between multiple sounds, and identifying sound patterns. Individuals may struggle to differentiate changes in speech, such as sarcasm, and may be affected by the order in which auditory information is presented. Additionally, their ability to synthesize sound clues meaningfully and act upon them might be compromised.

	Diagnosing CAPD involves systematic observation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests, which can be administered by various professionals, including audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. These tests may consist of questionnaires, auditory behavior observations, and advanced acoustic signal recordings. Despite efforts, no single test or cause for CAPD has been consistently identified.

Shakespeare's Twelfth Night suggests that while masquerade can be a tool for deceit over extended periods, it ultimately requires shedding the disguise to prevent self-forgetfulness. Disclosing the truth, however, poses challenges such as potential estrangement. The decision then lies between self-preservation and the maintenance of relationships. While some may accept the ruse, others may be offended.

The theme of deception in gender reversal, particularly Viola's case, raises significant concerns, namely the motive behind one's assumption of an opposite gender identity. Viola, a newcomer in a strange land, adopts a male guise for protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…" (5.1.247-249). Her scheme succeeds but distances her from female companions, denying her important support. Moreover, her convincing portrayal leads Olivia to confuse her with her twin brother Sebastian, resulting in romantic entanglements: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, she faces suppressed romantic feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261)

Viewed through a modern lens, this might be seen as an exploration of how deception can unveil hidden emotions, particularly for Olivia and Orsino. Some passages suggest these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires invoked by Viola/Cesario's presence. For example, is Olivia's attraction to Cesario due to his male appearance, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? One might argue Olivia's behavior suggests she is merely reflecting the societal judgments of her time. This is evident in her swift shift from Cesario to Sebastian and her newfound familial regard for Cesario/Viola: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

The sharp criticisms aimed at German colonial rule, especially its harsh treatment of the Ovaherero and Nama peoples in German South West Africa, are well-documented. Yet, reducing the colonial enterprise to such stark terms would disregard the heterogeneity of imperial governance and educational initiatives. The German colonial empire varied widely across its territories, exhibiting diverse ruling styles and educational systems. Upon assuming control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, the British encountered a considerable population of literate Africans, a testament to German educational endeavors in the region. However, the scenario in South West Africa (now Namibia) presented a markedly different picture. Unlike in East Africa, where the government actively participated in native education, the task of educating the indigenous population in South West Africa was largely delegated to missionary societies with limited state support. Notably, the German government invested heavily in the education of European settlers, establishing a system of state schools and providing substantial support to missionary schools for settlers. This educational disparity left a lasting impact on South West Africa, even after the end of German rule. While other German colonies boasted literate African populations, in South West Africa, "the vast majority remained uneducated and illiterate," due to a combination of social, political, and economic factors. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors, particularly focusing on recent research into the mindsets of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a plethora of literature on education within the German colonial empire, much of it written in German and emerging during or immediately after the colonial period. These early works primarily aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later works in English broadened the discourse through comparative analyses of education across various German colonies and more detailed examinations of specific aspects. These studies revealed significant variations in educational systems among different colonies. The most relevant to this paper is Cohen's comparison of educational systems in South West Africa and East Africa, which discusses factors contributing to their differences. Cohen attributes many unique features of South West Africa's educational system to its substantial settler population.

South West Africa, with a moderately temperate climate, was more favorable to European settlement compared to other German colonies, although much of the territory is arid. By 1913, South West Africa had nearly 15,000 European settlers, in contrast to the 5,336 in East Africa, the next largest settler colony.

The evolution of Popular Music has witnessed an expansive growth over the last century, encompassing an array of genres that amass a vast landscape. The challenge lies in attempting to enumerate all the genres, as each—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has propagated numerous sub- and sub-sub-genres. Notably, the sub-genre Heavy Metal rock has demonstrated remarkable diversity and emotional range over the past four decades. It is characterized by a broad spectrum of emotions, predominantly on the darker side. This diversity stems from the early recognition of Heavy Metal's flexibility, leading to the creation of unique sub-genres, which, in turn, birthed sub-sub-genres, continuing to this day.

The Heavy Metal movement today is so fragmented that it is difficult to pinpoint its core essence. It has assimilated themes from various genres, yet traces its origins to a specific starting point. To grasp the contemporary Heavy Metal music, one must first understand the movement's definition and its status as a movement rather than a mere genre.

Metal, in essence, is a movement characterized by darkness. It can be deemed the "music of more"—more bass, volume, aggression, and theatricality. Unlike its predecessors, Metal bands exhibit exceptional instrumental prowess. Moreover, the movement has been deeply entwined with drug culture, with the mid-70s psychedelic boom significantly influencing its evolution and sonic exploration. This association with drugs facilitated the creation of otherworldly recordings, often serving as a catalyst for the exploration of dark, visceral qualities, which were relatively untapped by mainstream popular music at the time. Furthermore, later generations of Metal have drawn inspiration from the dark, emotional depth of the Romantic era. Lyrics such as those from Helter Skelter by the Beatles exemplify this darker side, reflecting a journey through highs and lows, often attributed to drug influences. This song, considered one of the first Heavy Metal tracks, served as a response to The Rolling Stones' heavier, darker tracks, demonstrating the Beatles' desire to match their intensity.

Years prior to the inception of dreamlike works by Surrealist artists, Henri Rousseau was diligently weaving his own reveries, both literal and metaphorical. In 'The Dream,' a 1910 masterpiece by the renowned Post-Impressionist, we witness not merely a woman captivated by a landscaped dream, but also Rousseau’s own aspirations and internal conflict as a painter. Since embarking on his artistic journey, he harbored dreams of acceptance, admiration, and acclaim from peers and connoisseurs alike, grappling with the conundrum of either conforming to or emulating established painting styles for validation, or forging his own path, thus showcasing his unique creativity.

To fully understand 'The Dream' through this lens, one must first acquaint oneself with Rousseau’s life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, a French town in the northwest, his father was a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed a comfortable living. Lacking formal art training, Rousseau was employed as a gabelou until the age of forty, working for France's municipal toll service, earning the moniker 'douanier' or customs inspector. The loss of his first wife, Clémence, and their eight infant children left him with only his daughter, Julia, and profound sadness, pushing him to turn to painting for solace and renewal. Unlike peers who romanticized the peasant in art, Rousseau was a folk painter, his dreams reflecting those of the average working class.

Rousseau’s longing for acceptance in the art world becomes more palpable when considering his background: he was untrained, began late in life, and was active contemporaneously with esteemed artists. Recognition for his work, however, came around the same time Matisse was gaining prominence. In 'Modern French Painters,' author Jan Gordon notes that while both were competitors, they differed in style, subject matter, and motivation: “Matisse painted to avoid triviality, while Rousseau sought to create conventional art to gain admission to the Artiste Français” (92).

Throughout history, numerous intellects have contended that a profound bond exists between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I concur with this notion at a foundational level. John Keats, in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn", aptly captures this sentiment: "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." The knowledge we acquire in life primarily comes through formal education or life experiences. Yet, we seem to grasp the essence of ethics and aesthetics intuitively, as Keats suggests, without needing formal instruction. Both fields strive to elucidate rather than dictate. We delve into the reasons behind a piece's artistry or moral merit, rather than establish rules for creating or evaluating such works.

Critiques of art or morality often fall short of encapsulating the true nature of goodness or beauty. A discussion on the Mona Lisa's value might revolve around elements like perspective, composition, or cultural significance, but these fail to encapsulate why it's considered great art. More often than not, responses to a favorite work of art or literature begin with an enigmatic, inexplicable phrase like "There's just something about it," followed by a more detailed explanation. This implies that both art and morality possess an ineffable quality that transcends description. As Flannery O'Connor asserts, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Similarly, morality and ethics, despite our best efforts, cannot be fully articulated.

This ineffable quality, often referred to as "je ne sais quoi," is their most potent attribute. It is this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics that binds them together. I believe that both fields impact us at a level that is felt but not fully comprehended, a notion echoed by Immanuel Kant's concept of the "noumenal." This connection is especially strong in literature, as McKean posits, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is unique about the art, is its moral quality. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there." Thus, I propose that this shared transcendental nature of ethics and aesthetics is what forges their deep connection.

The contemporary Germany stands as a powerful entity, an amalgamation of cultural tapestries that unfurl from the alpine cradle of Munich to the Baltic seashore of Kiel. This cultural mosaic is evident from Cologne's riverine location, weaving through the nation's heart, and concluding in the Elbe-side city of Dresden in Saxony. Given this rich cultural blend, it is no surprise that the Germany we know today is a synthesis of diverse origins and tribal influences.

The ancestral home of the Germans, Germania, the etymology of its name remains a subject of scholarly debate. Some attribute the name to a Germanic tribe, the Tungrians, who were known as such before crossing the Rhine to face the Gallic forces (Tacitus, 98). Caesar, in his Commentaries on the Gallic War, initially used the term "Germanus" to delineate between the conquered Gauls and the Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC). The origin of the name remains uncertain, with some suggesting it derived from the Gallic word for neighbor, while others propose it comes from the old Anglo-Saxon term for spear, "ger," or the Old Irish "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans' reputation for loudness (Names of Germany).

Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," described the Germans as indigenous to the region, untouched by foreign immigration or contact. He posed the question, "Who would abandon a comfortable life in Asia or Africa to settle in Germany, with its harsh terrain, gloomy skies, and grim demeanor?" (Tacitus, 98). The Romans, for their part, rarely ventured into Germania, preferring instead to lead occasional campaigns and trade goods and skills acquired from the region. Thus, as Germanic tribes emerged in the first century, they remained on the empire's borders, trading their produce and military skills with the Romans (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

I gazed vacantly at the tableau before me, a blank slate. Impartially, steadfast, my consciousness parsed the image without attachment to any abstract concepts. Ideas flitted through my mind like leaves in a breeze, appearing and disappearing in an instant. My mind was a conduit, not a creator. At some point, I procured an instructional volume called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain," seeking to learn the art of drawing since my childhood. It offers insights into the mind's processes when interpreting lines and brushstrokes. One method it suggests is to impose a square frame around an image to simplify the scene. Yet, when I stood before the bowl of fruit and the expansive kitchen, I could not frame it as the artist's manual advised. I was paralyzed by awe, the masterpieces of Picasso and Monet dancing in my mind's eye. It was the genesis of my own artistic exploration, the inception of "Work in Brown." My fingers danced with the brush, my muscles tensed and released, my intent taking form. The water was serene, clear, and clean. Matter broke away, swallowed by the void. My hand struck the toilet handle again, my second attempt more urgent. The offending package remained stubborn. I held the mop loosely, feet planted, tie knotted around my neck, my brow furrowed as I stared at the unwanted deposit. A few more flushes, a few more moments of reflection, and my hand reached for the wall, grabbing the toilet paper, wrapping it around my glove like a glove. Standing tall, then bent at the waist, my hand dipped into the bowl, a mother's gentle hand reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Young adults often meet tragic ends behind the wheel. A convergence of several factors leads to this grim statistical trend for the youngest American drivers. According to the National Institutes of Health, one aspect of the issue is that the immature adolescent brain is not yet equipped to handle the perils of driving. Additionally, their lack of experience is a significant contributor to this problem. This inexperience not only increases the likelihood of fatal accidents but also leads to more rollovers, speeding incidents, and driving off the road. Teenagers, predictably, are more frequently accompanied by peers, which is known to be a norm. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center revealed a notable correlation between the age of the passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents. Many states, including California, have implemented temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours teens can drive and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, these measures are merely stopgap solutions. The core issue is that, collectively, the youngest drivers are statistically unable to manage the associated risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman argues that even 18 years of age might be too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports Zuckerman's findings that individuals under 19 or 20 often crave thrill-seeking experiences. Thus, delaying driving until these tendencies subside seems sensible. If we persist in issuing driver's licenses to young teens, we may witness an escalation in fatal accidents, with the death toll potentially reaching alarming proportions in the coming years. The Baby Boomers' children will soon become eligible to drive, adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads. Legislation addressing this concern could be relatively straightforward. Educational institutions could continue to teach driver's education, with no one under 18 allowed to drive a vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued, followed by a full driver's license after a certain number of hours of practical training. The specific number of hours required could mirror the majority of states' current standards (for example, California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Given the national scope of teenage driver fatalities, unified, nationwide legislation on this issue would be sensible and potentially effective in safeguarding teens across the country. This proposed legislation is not an unprecedented idea.

While perusing the Library of Congress's collection of vintage Edison films, I decided to examine all 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films typically employ creative editing to create illusions. My analysis mainly focused on describing the poetic elements prevalent in most trick films and exploring the unique characteristics of certain later films. Around the turn of the century, trick films were primarily confined within a stage-like setting, using a frontal proscenium with no camera movement. They typically employed long and medium shots, adhering to the single shot per film rule. However, some films in the early 1900s defied these conventions by incorporating multiple shots.

One common trait of trick films is their filming within a static frame, reminiscent of early theatre and vaudeville stages. The camera remains stationary, allowing figures and objects to move horizontally but rarely approach or recede from the lens. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth, but the camera doesn't track their movements. Similarly, shots are usually long or medium, with close-ups being absent, mirroring the theatre tradition where the audience views the entire performance within the stage's frame.

Most early trick films operate under the principle that one conceptual shot equals one film, limiting their length to about a minute or less. This practice also restricts their dramatic or narrative potential, with most films presenting brief, vaudeville-style tricks like magic or disappearing acts. However, in trick films, a single conceptual shot often consists of multiple physical shots joined together to create illusions, such as apparitions or vanishings. The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early trick film, illustrates this practice, where the headless Mary's physical shot begins midway through the film, despite appearing as one continuous shot to the viewer.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, was an early and zealous advocate for Republican ideals. While he was primarily an agrarian, his foray into politics shaped him into a steadfast champion of personal liberties and governance. His commitment to an agrarian society underpinned his views on sovereignty, constitutional law, and even the judiciary. His dedication to preserving and promoting agriculture as the most superior profession influenced his arguments on these matters.

Taylor held that the United States possessed a unique opportunity to establish an ideal governance system, as there were no entrenched traditions to impede this process. He firmly believed in the interdependence of natural human rights and that they should be impervious to government intervention. He argued that, in the absence of civilization, the strong and cunning would thrive, but in a civilized society, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must acknowledge the inherent goodness and evil within people. He maintained a rigid dualistic morality, asserting that "As government is wielded by men, all its virtues and vices must be human." (Ibid., pg. 167) He defined good principles as those that safeguard private property, enhance agriculture, and discourage capitalism. He believed that a government rooted in these principles would operate equitably, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by self-interest. He viewed self-interest as a natural human trait, but considered it evil when it led to sub-societies that exploited others. A good government was essential to control man's inherent evil, but it must be vigilantly watched to prevent the infiltration of bad principles.

Like many of his contemporaries, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He favored a minimal Federal government, with no additional rights or powers than those explicitly stated. He recognized that an expansive Federal government could be costly and potentially despotic. However, he believed that a literal interpretation could be corrupt if not guided by the intent of the Constitution's framers. Furthermore, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly describes the nation as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Upon revisiting Figure 17, a marked decline in commuter log submissions was observed in the third month. This prompted concerns about the potential causes. The arrival of winter at a New England campus could account for some of this drop, as commuting by bicycle or foot may have decreased. Additionally, December marks the end of the academic term, with students and faculty busied by end-of-semester tasks. The commuter log may have been overshadowed by these priorities. Furthermore, December's holiday season brings a temporary campus hiatus, further reducing the need to commute. The low February submissions remain unexplained. It's possible that projects like these experience an initial enthusiasm followed by a natural decline. To counter this, the Carpool Challenge Week, a March campaign, was introduced, which resulted in increased submissions. Maintaining project momentum, especially during holidays and semester breaks, was a significant challenge. Another hurdle was the cultural preference for driving, necessitating incentives for alternative commuting. Various prizes, including gift cards, were offered. While these were deemed sufficient initially, larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, could have further boosted participation. Varying prize values over time might have also helped.

ETFs, or exchange-traded funds, are financial instruments that aim to mirror indexes, commodities, or a selection of assets, much like index funds, but trade like stocks on exchanges. They offer diversification akin to index funds, along with the perks of stock ownership, such as short selling, margin buying, and single share transactions. Despite their appeal, ETFs charge lower fees compared to typical mutual funds. However, they incur trade commissions, similar to stock orders. The array of ETF options is broad, but it's prudent for astute investors to scrutinize these claims, especially diversification's extent. We'll examine ETF IHF and its top ten holdings, representing 63.58% of its assets, to gauge if owning the ETF matches the benefits of owning individual stocks, and if there are superior configurations for better performance.

To simplify, we'll focus on these top ten holdings. We'll assess their representativeness of the ETF by calculating their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Returns, assuming the portfolio mirrors the ETF's asset distribution. From these calculations, a portfolio of the top ten holdings yields a 6.11% higher return with a lower Beta of 0.12 compared to the ETF. This suggests a portfolio of these top stocks could offer higher returns and lower risk. However, statistical significance isn't guaranteed.

To evaluate if these portfolios differ significantly, we'll determine the standard deviation of each top ten stock and normalize it to 100% for a comparison with the ETF IHF's total standard deviation.

Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" is frequently cited as one of his more notable compositions. Within this poem, Poe employs the term "Thulé" in verses 6 and 56, a term traceable to Virgil's works. Virgil referenced Thulé as an island situated beyond the northern reaches of Britain, considered the boundary of known lands by the Greeks. Although Virgil's usage is undeniable, there's a more contemporary reference that merits attention. Poe had a strong affinity for German literature.

This use of "Thulé" carries significance as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt's book, "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," delves into the similarities between the two poets' works, concluding that Poe was likely imitating Goethe. Goethe, renowned for his poetic drama "Faust," published the first part in 1808 and the second part upon his death in 1832. Within the second part lies a poem entitled "The King of Thulé," chronicling a king who, after his wife's death, descends into alcoholism and despair, ultimately taking his own life. The similarities between the king and the description in "Dream-Land" are striking, mirroring Poe's own struggles with loss and addiction.

Poe's usage of "Thulé" extends beyond "Dream-Land." In "The Pit and the Pendulum," he employs the phrase "ultma Thulé," suggesting a connection to "The King of Thulé." "Dream-Land" and "The King of Thulé" can be viewed as complementary works. In "Dream-Land," the speaker's description of Thulé—a dark, lonely landscape haunted by friends—echoes the melancholic state of the king in Goethe's poem. This parallelism suggests that Poe may have stepped into the narrative of "The King of Thulé," mirroring his own emotional turmoil. Goethe's influence on Poe is further underscored by his reputation and connections to other notable figures like Tennyson, whose works Poe admired and whose circle he would have encountered.

In California, could an individual who suffered harm after slipping in a grocery store on spilled applesauce be awarded punitive damages, based on the store manager's awareness of past incidents and their inaction? A judge would likely not dismiss such a claim immediately. To claim punitive damages, the plaintiff must show that the defendant's actions were willfully and consciously disregarding probable harm, and that the conduct was despicable. In this case, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, could argue that the store manager, Paul Martin, should have known the potential harm of leaving the spill uncleaned, given the repeated incidents of customers slipping earlier. Although her argument about despicable conduct may not be strongest, it remains reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and the manager's lack of response. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, informed Martin of the spill, but he was on dinner break and declined to address it. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, reported the spill at 5:15 pm, but Martin again refused to act. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell, resulting in a serious back injury. By this time, five such incidents had already occurred that year. Palmer is now suing D&D for damages, and we are considering a motion for partial summary on the punitive damage claim. In California, punitive damages can be awarded for non-contractual breaches if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). Malice is defined as conduct intended to cause harm or, if no intent, conduct that is despicable and committed with a willful disregard for others' safety. Courts have considered conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable consequences of their actions and deliberately failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Back in 2019, I engaged in an educational exploration of Islam through a course at the Community Bible Church. The central debate that stirred our class was the nature of Islam, specifically if it was inherently antagonistic. This query feels even more pertinent today than it did at that time. Recall the seismic shifts in public perception of Islam and extremist groups post-9/11. The pendulum swung from a hostile stance to a nearly idolatrous tolerance. The notion of a president with the surname "Obama" being elected, with his familial roots in Islam, would have been unimaginable in 2001.

The life of the Prophet, as depicted in his biography, presents an intriguing conundrum. My understanding of historical Muhammad led me to believe he imposed Islam upon conquered tribes, yet the narrative paints him as a martyr, humbled and misunderstood. This portrayal leads people to seek out and embrace Islam on their own accord. I find a striking parallel between the ministries of Jesus and the miracles attributed to Muhammad. For instance, Muhammad's multiplication of sheep and milk to feed forty men echoes Jesus's feeding of the five thousand. This style of storytelling suggests Muhammad was divinely guided, not requiring validation through miracles, but merely embodying truth and wonder. This approach diminishes Jesus’s unique significance.

Moreover, many accounts in the biography feel contrived, aiming to substantiate witnesses or conversions independently. However, these stories are often filtered through multiple layers of hearsay, diminishing their credibility. I find it problematic that the biography elevates Muhammad as a paragon of godliness, humility, wisdom, and gentleness, which contradicts historical accounts of his conquests and rule.

This approach bothers me deeply. If Muslims are aware of the historical Muhammad, the true history behind his rise to power and subsequent rule, it may challenge the revered image of him as a gentle, humble leader.

The tenets expounded by Jesus during his tenure and the subsequent beliefs that emerged post-mortem, have evolved over time, shifting Christianity's trajectory away from its genesis. Observing this trajectory through a wide lens reveals a pattern of gradual deviation. Today's society demonstrates a heightened consciousness and an unprecedented inclination towards progress. While conservative factions persist, their impact on the whole is often negligible. Among Christians, historical awareness will burgeon in the coming years. A desire will spread, to differentiate the doctrines appended to Christianity over time from its original intent. This shift, though gradual, is inevitable: Christianity will revert to its essence, stripping away accumulated layers of doctrine, as if the clock is rewound. This reversion, sweeping through the United States and Europe, will inspire a new wave of adherents to worship as they did during Jesus' time, guided solely by his teachings. While the church's institutional strength will remain, the theological clock's backward movement will unify beliefs and practices, reducing diversity. This phenomenon is not unprecedented; history abounds with such reversals. For instance, Christianity once faced persecution under the Roman Empire, which later became a bastion of Christianity. The same country that once practiced African-American slavery now boasts African-American leadership. The Christian religion's future reversion will reverberate similarly, undoing history in its pursuit of authenticity and minimizing diversity. This process hinges on interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So, what transpired post-Jesus' life?

Retracing history, we find Judaism, Christianity's theological forebear, at its core. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the supremacy of Hebrew scriptures were entrenched by the time Rome seized Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish populace was not unified; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the general population.

I contend that Upton Sinclair's "The Jungle" illustrates the innate avarice and egoism within human nature. Individuals are inherently driven to prioritize their own interests and well-being, disregarding those beneath them. The novel underscores this theme through various examples. One prominent instance involves the proprietors and overseers of the colossal factories. Their singular objective is to maximize their enterprises, without concern for any obstacle or consequence. Sinclair vividly depicts the environmental fallout, as "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery highlights the owners' disregard for potential victims, both human and animal. They remain unperturbed by the factory's toxic emissions or the fetid waste runoff from the extensive pens surrounding Packingtown. The workers, too, are exploited, with their labor exploited to increase profits. The text notes, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers are subjected to grueling hours and sudden mass layoffs without compensation or job assistance. In this time, scant regulations safeguarded workers' safety or welfare, allowing managers and owners to operate unchecked. The rigors of the system were such that those who perished in Packingtown were expected to endure the harsh conditions both within the factories and in their surroundings. No entities existed to aid workers, and while unions were formed, they frequently exacerbated the plight of their members. The workers, trapped in this system, were likened to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

Authors, in their literary endeavors, often employ various methods to evoke specific sentiments or viewpoints regarding pivotal subjects. Some of these strategies are more successful than others. In his masterpiece, The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald employs numerous techniques to achieve this. He often combines adjectives and nouns in unconventional pairings to create an atmosphere around a subject. At times, he imbues symbols with meaning and uses them for the same purpose. Fitzgerald utilizes this latter technique extensively, particularly with colors such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald assigns significance to these colors and later employs them to convey feelings associated with important objects.

The meaning Fitzgerald ascribes to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher, more refined status and gray signifying older, faded elements. He establishes this significance early in the novel, using both colors repeatedly. Daisy and Jordan are frequently depicted in white—Daisy in particular, as seen when she is “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster” (74). Similarly, characters like Nick, Tom, and Catherine are often dressed in white, such as Nick’s “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party or Tom’s “white shirt” (36) during his encounter with Myrtle. The only time white is not predominant is when Nick describes Gatsby’s party as having “gaudy primary colors” (40). Additionally, Fitzgerald uses white/gray to color ordinary subjects: Nick's commute takes him “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), and the names on his party guest list are “gray” (61). The valley of ashes is filled with “gray cars” (23) and “gray land” (23), and even the dog-seller is a “gray old man” (27). After investing these colors with meaning, Fitzgerald employs them to signify unimportance or uniformity, beginning with Daisy. After a prolonged period without their use, Daisy is described as “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster,” portraying her more as a uniform addition rather than a character. This technique is further applied to Daisy, as seen in her “gray haze of fur collar” (18) and another white dress (115), emphasizing her role as an object of desire rather than a distinct individual.

San Diego County stands out for its agricultural prowess, largely due to its temperate and sun-drenched climate. Staple crops encompass tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. A thriving demand exists for organic community-supported agriculture in the San Diego region, with numerous local groups boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms extend tours of their operations and offer recreational activities such as hiking and birdwatching. This setup allows landowners to capitalize on government programs while enhancing habitats for recreation and educational purposes.

Organic farming, while filling a profitable niche market, is accompanied by increased costs and labor demands. It requires meticulous manual management to control pests and weeds, and lacking chemical assistance, soil fertilization becomes more labor-intensive. Consequently, organic farming often experiences higher losses compared to conventional methods. Additionally, small-scale organic farms lack the operational efficiency of larger entities. Benefits not directly linked to organic farming, such as planting cover crops, controlling invasive species, and manipulating plant growth to create specific habitats, can also add to labor costs.

The selected parcel, located near Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, is a 160-acre expanse of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland bordering the Cleveland National Forest. It falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, currently recognizing over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and certain butterfly species. Others, such as the California gnatcatcher, are on the verge of listing due to declining populations.

Historically, this land was inhabited by Native Americans for millennia, later settled by cattle ranchers and lumber operators in the late 1800s. As part of an original homestead patent, the land was likely used for grazing and wood production for many years. An examination of real estate listings led to the selection of this property for further research into available government programs. As a hypothetical model for farming this land, I identified a nearby organic farm.

Cultural dynamics significantly influence the negotiation process. Culture can be viewed not only by what it embodies but also by what it eschews, and the meanings it conveys. It is not a monolithic entity, nor is it singular or standardized. Propositions such as "all Russians are rigid" or "all Japanese are adaptable" are oversimplifications. While recognizing the broad strokes of a culture is beneficial, a successful negotiator should delve into the nuances of how a culture's attitudes can shape the negotiation dynamics at hand. When engaging with an unfamiliar culture, it is natural to draw comparisons based on one's own cultural lens, but it is crucial to understand that these comparisons may not always hold true.

Grasping a foreign culture or mindset can involve various approaches, from historical study to acknowledging its biases. Rather than passing judgment or attempting to alter a culture, one must recognize and respect its inherent values and work within its parameters, especially in negotiations where a weaker bargaining position exists.
